Increasing cooperation in agricultural households: Experimental evidence
 from maize farming households in Uganda
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
Smallholder agriculture households are composed of different individuals,
 each with their own preferences and access to resources, operating in a
 context governed by particular norms and beliefs.
 This realization resulted in many interventions aimed at strengthening
 the bargaining position of women within the household.
 At the same time, the household is also the predominant unit of production
 in which cooperation, specialization and investment in common goods may
 lead better outcomes.
 Instead of pitching spouses against each other, test two interventions
 designed to increase spousal cooperation.
 The first targets cognitive channels and estimates the impact of reducing
 differences in the information available to each spouse.
 The second targets non-cognitive skills, encouraging household members
 to approach maize farming as a household business, thereby challenging
 social norms and gender stereotypes that men and women should engage in
 different activities.
 We find that reducing intra-household information asymmetries increases
 joint decision making, reduces the labor time gap between spouses, increases
 the intention to jointly invest in agriculture, and increases communication
 among spouses.
 We find no effects on household level production outcomes.
 We find no effect of promoting a household cooperative approach to maize
 farming.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In semi-subsistence agriculture, the prevailing unit of production is the
 agricultural household.
 However, these households consist of different household members, each
 with their own utility functions and access to resources.
 The preferences of the different household members may not perfectly align,
 and there may be considerable inequality in access to resources 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "alderman1995unitary"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Research shows that this often results in inefficient allocation of production
 factors within these households.
 For instance, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "udry1996gender"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 finds significant differences in productivity between male-managed and
 female-managed plots due to the fact that more fertilizer and labor is
 allocated to man managed plots.
 Given diminishing returns to especially fertilizer use, he finds that reallocat
ing production factors from man managed to women managed plots may increase
 household level productivity by 6 percent.
 The realization that household members compete as well as cooperate has
 led to a burgeoning literature grounded in collective bargain theory, with
 the important policy implication being that interventions may have different
 impact depending on who is targeted within the household 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "New1,haddad1997intrahousehold"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 Many interventions started to target women within households with the aim
 of strengthening their bargaining position vis-a-vis men.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recently, the focus has shifted somewhat, focusing less on intra-household
 competition and more on cooperation between household members.
 This is partly due to the fact that alternative models of the household
 have been proposed that provide more room for intra-household cooperation.
 For example, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "doss2015collective"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 point out that households face collective action problems similar to those
 studied in the context of common pool resources management.
 Furthermore, innovations in gender disaggregated data collection such as
 the Women Empowerment in Agriculture Index (WEAI) show that many resources
 are jointly owned and decisions jointly made, and so the clear division
 between man managed and women managed plots underlying bargaining models
 may be the exception rather that the rule 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "alkire2013women,doss2014owns,twyman2015gendered,doi:10.1111/dpr.12243"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 For some time now, the literature on measuring women empowerment has been
 stressing that unilateral decisions made by a women within the household
 should not always be strictly preferred to instances where decisions are
 taken together.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this paper, we document patterns of cooperation between male- and female
 co-heads in monogamous smallholder farm households in Uganda.
 We also test two different strategies to improve cooperation between spouses.
 Each strategy targets a different impact pathway.
 A first intervention that we will test involves reducing information asymmetrie
s within households.
 Informational frictions are important barriers to agricultural technology
 adoption and sustainable intensification 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "magruder2018assessment"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 Access to information and ensuing knowledge may be unequally distributed
 between spouses within the household, which may reduce the likelihood that
 spouses cooperate in an effective way.
 In particular, if one spouse has information while the other has not, he
 or she may be more inclined to take decisions unilaterally as he of she
 feels the other is unqualified.
 If both spouses have equal information, spouses may be more open to each
 other's advise.
 We thus compare spousal cooperation in households in which information
 was made available to only one of the spouses—the husband or wife—to cooperatio
n in households in which this information was made available to both spouses.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The second strategy consists of promoting a mental image of farming as a
 joint venture, with both spouses having an equal role in decision making,
 activities, and rewards.
 Farming happens in a particular cultural context, and social norms may
 hamper efficient allocation of production factors.
 For instance, in patrilineal societies it may be that only men are assumed
 to make decisions on certain crops, or only women are allowed to carry
 out certain activities.
 However, norms and customs can change, and role models have been found
 to be important catalysts 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "porter2019gender"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 We therefore devise an intervention aimed at promoting a cooperative approach
 to farming by the household.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Central to both treatments are short, engaging videos that were produced
 with a dual purpose.
 First, the videos are designed to provide information on a range of yield
 increasing agricultural management practices such as timely planting, seed
 spacing and seed rate, and strategies to deal with striga, a parasitic
 weed that is a major threat to maize in the area.
 The videos also recommend the use of modern inputs such as fertilizer and
 improved seed.
 Second, the videos are designed to change a range of non-cognitive personality
 traits, such as aspirations, locus-of-control, and attitudes to change
 of the persons that view the video.
 In particular, the videos bring the story of a farmer that used to struggle
 with low maize yields and decides things need to change.
 It is then shown how the farmer uses recommended practices and improved
 inputs.
 It is explained that becoming a successful farmer takes time, and money
 needs to be invested incrementally to get better results in the future.
 The video ends with the image of a successful farmer assuring the viewer
 that he or she can also become successful by following the advice provided
 in the video.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The main subject of the paper, and primary outcome in the field experiment,
 is cooperation between spouses within the household.
 Different strands of the literature have different conceptualizations of
 cooperation within the household, and why it is important.
 In the context of non-separable agricultural household models alluded to
 above, cooperation is often cast as pareto-efficiency increasing options
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Which may imply spouses specialize in certain activities.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 In lab-in-the-field experiments with households, cooperation is equated
 with maximizing a social optimum.
 In more recent observational studies that collect gender disaggregated
 data, and in light of the substantial evidence against unitary household
 models, cooperation is increasingly assessed in terms of joint decision
 making and balance in contributions.
 In this literature, qualitative aspects of cooperation between spouses
 such including overburdening and drudgery in labour or heterogeneity in
 decision making (eg relative strength of voice in decision making) becomes
 important.
 This study mostly sees cooperation as joint decision making and equal contribut
ions in terms of labour, although we also look at household level efficiency.
 We also explore the impact pathways by looking if households communicate
 more and how they handle disagreement.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We find that the first intervention—reducing intra-household information
 asymmetries—increases joint decision making on a range of agronomic practices.
 We also find that there is an increase in the likelihood that spouses jointly
 decide to use fertilizer.
 The intervention also reduces the gap between labor time contributed by
 the wife and labor time contributed by the husband.
 Furthermore, reducing intra-household information asymmetries increases
 the likelihood that both spouses prioritize investment in agriculture.
 There is also evidence that spouses are more likely to tell each other
 if they disagree about something related to agriculture when information
 asymmetry is reduced.
 We find no effects on household level production outcomes.
 The second intervention—projecting a cooperative approach to maize farming—does
 not appear to have much impact.
 This may be because farmers are unable to identify with the role models
 in the video.
 It may also be that the treatment is too light to have an impact through
 non-cognitive pathways.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The remainder of the paper is organized as follows: The next section presents
 the research questions, the interventions we use to test the research hypothese
s, and the underlying theory of change.
 We then present the experimental design.
 Next, we turn to the results, first looking at how the interventions affect
 joint decision making.
 We then test if the interventions also leads to a more equitable distribution
 of labor.
 We also look at the impact of the interventions on intentions to invest
 proceeds from maize farming and explore household level production outcomes.
 A next section explores spousal disagreement and we also report effects
 on the likelihood that farmers tell each other in the event of disagreement.
 A final section concludes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Research questions and theory or change
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We investigate two likely barriers to spousal cooperation among smallholder
 maize farmers in Uganda.
 The first is unequal access to information as a production factor and the
 second is related to the cultural context in which traditions and norms
 dictate behaviour.
 We discuss each in turn.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Information as a productive resource
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Often, the poor appear to make sub-optimal decision because they lack critical
 pieces of information, fail to notice 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "34"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, or hold beliefs that are not true 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "jensen2010perceived,dupas2011teenagers"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 Therefore, in many instances, information campaigns designed to address
 these information inefficiencies can make a big difference 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "banerjee2011poor"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 Also in the context of smallholder agriculture, it has been argued that
 a lack of information about the existence, use, and profitability of modern
 inputs and recommended practices is a major constraint to sustainable crop
 intensification 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "de2017field,magruder2018assessment"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 Due to its public, non-rival nature, agricultural extension information
 is generally under-supplied by the private sector, and so governments across
 the developing world have started to provide extension information as a
 public service.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Information as a critical production factor is likely to be unequally distribute
d within the household.
 Information may benefit one spouse more than the other, may be monopolized,
 or hidden from the other spouse 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "10.1257/aer.104.7.2210"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 A large literature underscores the importance of social networks for agricultur
al technology adoption, which may be segregated according to sex 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "BEAMAN2018147,MEKONNEN2018321"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 Extension services often target the farmer-landowner or the household head,
 which is generally the male co-head.
 The assumption that extension messages targeting one household member will
 trickle down to the rest of the household, including women and younger
 household members, may be false 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "fletschner2011gender"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is some evidence that suggest that a more equal distribution of knowledge
 within the households leads to better outcomes, potentially due to more
 cooperation.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "lambrecht2016agricultural"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 investigate the effect of participating in extension training as a couple.
 They investigate whether inclusion of female farmers in an agricultural
 extension programme in South-Kivu increases adoption of three technologies
 at the household level: improved legume varieties, row planting and mineral
 fertilizer.
 In their study, joint male and female programme participation leads to
 the highest adoption rates.
 The lab-in-the-field experiment of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "ashraf2009spousal"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 shows how decision making is greatly influenced by the extent to which
 information is shared between spouses.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One hypothesis we will test is therefore whether reducing information asymmetrie
s between spouses may lead to more cooperative outcomes.
 There are various reasons why this may be the case.
 If only one spouse has access to information, the other may be excluded
 from decision making because he or she may be considered unqualified.
 It may be that when both spouses receive information, spouses discuss and
 reflect on this information, making it more likely that they also decide
 and act upon it jointly.
 In addition, a reduction in information asymmetry also reduces the ability
 to monopolize or conceal information by one of the spouses.
 Borrowing from research on common pool resource management, if both spouses
 have information, they can monitor each other, which strengthens incentives
 for contributions to the common (household level) goods and discourages
 over-consumption 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "doss2015collective"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Social norms and gender stereotypes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Smallholder agricultural production does not happen in a vacuum.
 Smallholders are generally located in remote areas, where customs and norms
 that prescribe 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

desirable
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 behavior still play an important role.
 In close-knit societies, what individuals can and can not do often depends
 on how others, including one's spouse, judge it.
 There is a large literature on how cultural values and gender norms are
 important determinants of women’s work choices 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "eg."
key "10.1093/qje/qjv001,10.2307/27804976"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 More recently, research also started to look into the intra-household dynamics
 that mediate the role that norms play, as the cost of violating norms may
 differ between spouses and/or there may be important externalities 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "10.1257/pandp.20181086,10.1257/aer.20180975"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Several studies point out the importance of role models to behaviour change
 in context of strong norms and beliefs.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "porter2019gender"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 show that role models can be effective in increasing women participation
 in sectors that are traditionally dominated by men.
 In the context of economic development, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "campos2015breaking"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 document female entrepreneurs who succeed in male-dominated sectors in
 Uganda, and also point out the importance of exposure to role models to
 circumvent or overcome the norms that maintain occupational segregation.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "nguyen2008information"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 finds that in Madagascar, a role model sharing her life story at a school
 significantly increased student's test performance.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "bernard2019parental"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "bernard2015will"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 study how videos of role models may have long run effects in Ethiopia.
 Finally, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "riley2017increasing"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 shows that the inspirational story of a Ugandan girl from a slum that goes
 on to become a world chess champion (as chronicled in the Disney feel-good
 movie 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Queen of Katwe
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) positively impacted test results of Ugandan school girls.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As a second hypothesis, we will therefore test whether projecting a cooperative
 approach to household farming leads to more cooperative outcomes.
 Also here, we posit different impact pathways.
 First, there may be aspirational effects of seeing a couple farming maize
 successfully together.
 The intervention may also serve to challenge social norms and gender roles
 that prescribe that men specialize in productive and women in reproductive
 activities.
 This may lead women to become more assertive when men take decisions or
 it may make men more open to women participation in farming, leading to
 more joint decision making and a more equitable division of farm labour.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Interventions and Experimental design
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Both experiments are implemented using short videos that were shown to farmers
 on tablet computers during a private meeting.
 The video was shown twice to our study participants, once before the maize
 planting time (July 2017) and once around the actual time of planting time
 (August 2017).
 The videos were designed with a dual purpose in mind.
 First, the videos serve to transfer knowledge about recommended agronomic
 management practices and the use of modern technologies.
 It is shown how fields need to be prepared using organic fertilizer.
 Proper seed spacing and seeding rates and it importance are explained.
 Furthermore, it is shown in detail how inorganic fertilizer needs to be
 applied and in what quantities.
 Attention is also devoted to identifying striga, a parasitic weed that
 affects maize yields in the area.
 The importance of seed quality receives ample attention as well and using
 hybrid seed or Open Pollinated Varieties (OPV) is recommended.
 Other recommended practices include timely planting and weeding.
 Second, the information was packaged as an inspirational story of poor
 farmers that, over time, are able to break out of a poverty trap.
 The video starts with a farmer explaining that he used to struggle with
 low yields, producing barely enough food to feed his family, but that over
 the years, he learned how to increase the number of bags of maize produced
 on his maize plots.
 It is shown how the farmer starts using recommended practices on a small
 part of his land.
 It is also shown how he sells a chicken and borrows some money from a neighbor
 to buy improved seed and fertilizer.
 The return on this initial investment is then re-invested, and the viewer
 is taken through some basic inter-temporal cost-benefit calculations.
 The video ends by showing a happy farmer that assures the viewer that he
 or she can also become a successful farmer by following his example.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To answer the first research question—whether reducing information asymmetry
 within households is effective for more cooperative outcomes—we compare
 outcomes of households in which the couple (husband and wife together)
 is shown a video to outcomes of households in which with only one co-head
 of the household (husband or wife) is shown the video.
 To answer the second research question—whether promoting a household cooperativ
e approach to farming is effective—we compare outcomes of households where
 an aspirational video was shown in which a man and woman participate as
 equals on the family farm and deliver the message as a couple to outcomes
 of households where where an aspirational video was shown featuring only
 a man.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The field experiment was carried out among a random sample of maize farmers
 in eastern Uganda.
 Two-stage cluster sampling was used to obtain a representative sample of
 this population.
 In particular, from five districts (Bugiri, Mayuge, Iganga, Namayingo,
 and Namutumba), we first selected 50 rural parishes randomly and in proportion
 to the number of villages within each parish.
 In the selected parishes, all villages were included in the study.
 Within each village, we then listed all the households, from which we sampled
 10 households to be included in the study.
 A total of 3,303 households participated in the first experiment; 2,209
 in the second experiment.
\end_layout

