\begin_layout Section
Conclusion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Increased cooperation among spouses may render preferences of the individual
 members more aligned and lead to a more efficient allocation of resources.
 Perhaps more importantly than efficiency considerations, there is intrinsic
 value in a balanced workload and shared agency between spouses within the
 household.
 We test two strategies to increase cooperation between spouses.
 One directly targets the asymmetry of information between spouses related
 to recommended practices and modern inputs for agricultural production.
 Information related to crop management, an important determinant of sustainable
 intensification, is generally provided to only one individual, under the
 assumption that information flows freely within the household.
 In a first treatment, we assess the impact on a range of outcomes of providing
 information to the couple (husband and wife together) versus providing
 this same information to only one individual (husband or wife).
 A second strategy targets gendered norms and customs, as in patriarchal
 societies, these may prevent the efficient allocation of resources within
 households.
 Therefore, in a second treatment, we promoted a cooperative approach to
 household farming and assess the impact on a range of outcomes of showing
 an aspirational video of a couple farming and providing the extension informati
on together versus showing a video in which a male farmer provides the same
 extention information .
 We do this using a field experiment involving 3,300 maize growing households
 in eastern Uganda.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We start by looking at decision making and confirm findings from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "doss2014owns"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 who find that many of the decisions in agriculture in Uganda are already
 taken jointly.
 Still, in most cases the man is still the predominant decision maker, especiall
y if monetary outlays are involved, such as the decision to use fertilizer
 or improved seed.
 Reducing information asymmetry between spouses significantly increases
 joint decision making related to the decision to plant maize on the plot,
 on strategies to fight striga, and on the timing of the first weeding.
 There is also some evidence that reducing information asymmetry increases
 joint decision making related to the use of fertilizer.
 No effects are found from projecting a cooperative approach to household
 farming, the second treatment.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Next, we look at labor time allocations of husband and wife with respect
 to maize farming.
 Women tend to work more than men but we find that the gap between woman
 labor and man labor reduces after reducing information asymmetry.
 While we find suggestive evidence that the husband works more on land preparati
on and harvesting, the effects are driven by a decrease in the labor supply
 of the wife.
 Also here, we find no impact of promoting a household cooperative approach.
 We further find that households where information was distributed among
 both spouses are more likely to indicate the intention to invest in agriculture.
 As increased cooperation was expected to increase overall efficiency, we
 also look at household level agricultural production related outcomes.
 In particular, we test if household level knowledge about recommended practices
 and modern inputs is affected by the two treatments.
 We also look at differences in adoption of a range of practices and inputs.
 A third family of household level outcomes we consider is related to maize
 production itself, and we test if our interventions have impacted household
 level welfare.
 We do not find impact of any of the treatments on any of these household
 level outcomes.
 Finally, we expect that spouses communicate more if they are encouraged
 to cooperate.
 Here, we do find that households where information asymmetry was reduced
 are more likely to tell each other when they do not agree with the other
 about a particular maize related issue.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Overall, we conclude that the first treatment which aimed to reduce information
 asymmetry between spouses about good agronomic practices for maize production
 was successful in increasing cooperation between spouses in some regards.
 Joint decision making about strategic agricultural decisions increased,
 which may increase the likelihood that the joint household utility function
 will be maximized 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "mcpeak2006household"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Spouses also became also more likely to express any disagreement about
 decisions related to maize production.
 The labor allocations by wife and husband became somewhat more balanced,
 particularly through a reduction in labor time by women, who tend to be
 the ones with the heaviest work burden.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The null results we obtain from the second treatment promoting a cooperative
 approach to household farming across the board are at odds with findings
 in other studies on role model effects.
 Most likely, this is due to the fact that the exposure to the role models
 was not intensive enough: while the videos were engaging, they were only
 about 10 minutes long.
 Other studies use movies of over one hour, or repeated exposure to role
 models 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "riley2017increasing"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 In addition, there are some indications that the farmers that were enrolled
 in the study had difficulty identifying with the actors, as most perceived
 them to be quite different from themselves.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, the fact that we do not find effects on the efficiency of household
 level agricultural production does not mean that efforts to increase cooperatio
n are futile.
 There may be impact in the future given that we find a significant increase
 in joint investment in agriculture.
 The only impact of reducing information asymmetry on the efficiency household
 level agricultural production is an increase in organic fertilizer use,
 which contributes to long run soil health.
\end_layout

